Interface SOCMessageForGame

    public interface SOCMessageForGame
    This indicates that a SOCMessage type is always about a particular game named in the message, or never about that game.

    Before adding to a per-game message queue, check that getGame() is not null or SOCMessage.GAME_NONE.

    Most implementing types' constructors will always require a game; some abstract subclasses such as SOCMessageTemplateMi may allow null, leaving the choice to each of their own subclasses. Non-abstract message types must always return a game name or SOCMessage.GAME_NONE from getGame(), never null.

    Template classes such as SOCMessageTemplateMi are convenient for quickly developing a new message type, but they all implement SOCMessageForGame. If the template classes are used for non-game data with a server, the server will use SOCMessage.GAME_NONE as the "game name".

    Since:
    1.1.11
    Author:
    Jeremy D Monin

    • Method Detail

      • getGame

        java.lang.String getGame()
        Name of game this message is for, if any. Must not be null in a message sent to the server: If message is not about per-game structures or code, use SOCMessage.GAME_NONE.

        At the server, the message treater dispatches incoming SOCMessageForGames based on their getGame():

        • null: Message is ignored
        • SOCMessage.GAME_NONE: Message is handled by SOCServer itself or SOCServerMessageHandler
        • Any other game name: Looks for a game with that name, to dispatch to the GameHandler for that game's type. If no game with that name is found, the message is ignored.
        Returns:
        the name of the game, or SOCMessage.GAME_NONE or (rarely, at client) null if none.

      • getType

        Get the message type. Implemented in SOCMessage.
        Returns:
